{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511185","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511185"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:39:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:39:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11713"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583551"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:18:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:18:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11713"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11713"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.14,0.02,0.71,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4328"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108108"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4328"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11713"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90518"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"492"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4986"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4989"},{"type":"tags","id":"4990"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5646"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11645"},{"type":"tags","id":"11648"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5902"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7809"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10037"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11267"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44844"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108108","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108108"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA general practitioner is about to review one of his regular patients who presented with abdominal pain and weight loss. The patient is 62-years old and is usually in good health. A CT scan was arranged and shows a mass in the stomach suspicious for carcinoma as well as lesions with the liver suspicious for metastases.  Through the doctor\u0027s longstanding relationship with the patient and their family, he understands the family\u0027s deeply protective nature. As anticipated, the family has expressed a strong desire to shield the patient from any distressing information.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one the following is the most appropriate initial action for the general practitioner to take?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Discuss the likely diagnosis with the family, and allow them to inform the patient when and how they would like to.","Inform the patient of their cancer diagnosis and their associated prognosis in a private environment.","Refer the patient to another specialist for more information and support","Have a private discussion with the patient to understand their preferences about receiving medical information","Arrange for further testing to confirm the diagnosis prior to any discussions about potential diagnoses."],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis passage evaluates candidates\u0027 ability to handle communication challenges and ethical considerations in healthcare, especially regarding disclosing medical information to patients and their families.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere may be multiple reasons why the patient\u0027s family may not initially want the \u0027bad news\u0027 to be disclosed to the patient, including cultural differences surrounding medical autonomy. In Australia, patient autonomy is a core ethical principle that informs doctors\u0027 clinical decisions. In this instance, despite what the family are saying, our duty of care is with the patient and it is important to act in their best interests. However, it is also important to take the time to understand the family\u0027s point of view. Taking the time to understand the family\u0027s point of view and showing respect towards the family\u0027s perspective can help to establish a positive relationship with the family. It is important to keep in mind that the family\u0027s desire to withhold information likely comes from a desire to protect the patient. As such, establishing this relationship early can help to de-escalate tensions and create an opportunity to address their concerns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUltimately, the doctor\u0027s responsibility is to do the best for their patient. As part of respecting patient autonomy,\u003Cstrong\u003E it is important to discuss with the patient what their preferences are on receiving information\u003C/strong\u003E - including\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Ehow much they would like to know about their health and diagnosis, as well as which information they would like shared with their family.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWith the preferences of both the patient and family in mind, the doctor can then take steps towards effectively and incrementally sharing the necessary clinical information as part of their professional obligation. Having a conversation together with both the patient and their family can be a productive way to help the doctor understand these varying opinions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs a practical takeaway for breaking bad news to patients in this situation, it can be done incrementally using the SPIKES model (setup, perception, invitation, knowledge, empathise, summarise) so as to minimise any distress to the patient or their family.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiscuss the likely diagnosis with the family\u003C/strong\u003E is not an appropriate answer option as it does not take patient preference into account and undermines their autonomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInform the patient of their cancer diagnosis and their associated prognosis in private\u003C/strong\u003E assumes the patient wants to know the presumptive diagnosis, and disregards family wishes, which may cause unnecessary rapport loss and conflict.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERefer the patient to another specialist for more information and support\u003C/strong\u003E is an eventually necessary step, but it does not address the immediate communication needs. As part of the patient\u0027s treating team, the general practitioner should also bear the responsibility of providing bad news.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArrange for further tests to confirm the diagnosis\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate response as it does not address immediate communication needs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor more information on how to manage family requests of withholding the diagnosis, please refer to the article in the \u0022References\u0022 section.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The patient\u0027s desires should be the doctor\u0027s priority.","Using the SPIKES model can help to incrementally break bad news in an empathetic way."],"references":["McCabe, M.S., Wood, W.A. and Goldberg, R.M., 2010. When the family requests withholding the diagnosis: who owns the truth?. Journal of Oncology Practice, 6(2), p.94.McCabe MS, Wood WA, Goldberg RM. When the family requests withholding the diagnosis: who owns the truth?. Journal of Oncology Practice. 2010 Mar;6(2):94.","Hagerty, RG, Butow PN, Ellis PM, Dimitry S, Tattersall MHN. Communicating prognosis in cancer care: a systematic review of the literature. Annals of Oncology [Internet]. 2005 July [cited 2024 May 1]; 16(7): 1005-1053. Available from: https://doi.org/10.1093/annonc/mdi211","Matthews T, Baken D, Ross K, Ogilvie E, Kent L. The experiences of patients and their family members when receiving bad news about cancer: A qualitative meta-synthesis. Psycho-Oncology [Internet]. 2019 Oct 16 [cited 2024 May 1];28(12):2286-2294. Available from: https://doi.org/10.1002/pon.5241"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90518"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11713"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90518","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90518"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-06T20:46:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-06T20:46:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4328"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108108"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioethics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.